Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A presumption against routing rights of way through farmyards and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">other areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> - on the grounds of safety, security and nuisance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A set period after use has ceased that an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘established use’ application</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> can be made to register a right of way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’,</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Fees or deposits for applications to record or alter a right of way on a definitive map</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reasonable limits on fees charged on applications for Public Path Orders,</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Enabling the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gating of rights of way on the grounds of security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, e.g. to prevent vehicular access on a footpath,</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An improvement in the quality of evidence to justify claims for a right of way.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU supports clause 43 of the draft Bill which will enable the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Gangmasters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Licencing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Authority to have access to Enforcement Undertaking civil sanctions in addition to their current powers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU agrees in principle with Clause 58</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> providing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a standard “contribute to economic growth and prosperity duty”, which s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hould apply to all regulators.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Clauses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> 12-18 &amp; Schedule 6: Rights of way</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The continued</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">discovery of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">laims for rights of way on members’ land can pose significant financial and psychological stress on the landowner affected as well as imposing significant practical constraints on farming practices.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Such claims can either be for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the discovery of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">historic unrecorded routes that may have existed prior to 1949 or from claims based on a 20 year period of established use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Some members have faced multiple claims for rights of way over their land, sometimes based on limited or inaccurate evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and have been provided with little scope to enable more practical routes or conditions to be found</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that take account of current land use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Defending themselves against such claims can prove both costly and stressful, not helped by the protracted nature of the process, which can mean claimed routes remain open to challenge for many years.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evident</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the current suite of legislation for claiming rights of way is in need of reform </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to provide clarity to both land </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">/managers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rights of way </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">users and provide suitable defences for landowners facing spurious claims.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU is therefore supportive of the suite of measures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contained within the draft Deregulation Bill regarding rights of way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Clauses 12-18 and Schedule 6. These clauses deliver th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ose</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recommendations of the a Stakeholder Working Group on Unrecorded Rights of Way’s repor