 package of measures within the Draft Deregulation Bill we think there are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">additional reforms to rights of way legislation which would merit inclusion and meet the spirit of the Bill’s measures to reduce the burden of regulation on society and public bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. These are discussed in paragraphs 11 to 28.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A presumption against routing rights of way through farmyards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> buildings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> including homes</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU strongly supports the inclusion of provisions in the draft Deregulation Bill (Schedule 6, Paragraph 5) for the m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">odification of the definitive map by consent, where both the landowners accept that the route should be added to the definitive map, and are happy to consent to the proposal subject to agreed modifications to the route. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is essential to enable historical routes to be fitted within current land use needs, e.g.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> avoid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an area where there ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e a lot of machinery movements.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, for pragmatic decisions to be made consistently in such cases there</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is a need for a presumption within primary legislation in favour of diverting paths away from farmyards and other areas where safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and nuisance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are an issue. Such a presumption would assist Surveying Authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">avoid diversions of a route from being defeated simply because a route follows an historic line.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cases exist where farmers have applied to divert footpaths away from their busy farmyard onto an alternative route (often an existing and well-used permissive path around the buildings). However, despite having the support of the highways authority, objections on the basis that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">route was a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> historic one, and therefore should not be altered, have led the planning inspector to find that such diversions should not be granted. In some instances this is despite a local authority already possessing a local policy to divert in such circumstances.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A presumption in legislation would improve the safety and enjoyment of rights of way users in the countryside, reduce conflicts between farming practice and users, reduce bureaucratic burden on local  authorities by reducing the risk of objections, and reduce the stress and burden placed on land managers by rights of way passing through inappropriate areas. Such a presumption should be able to be waived at the discretion of the landowner/occupier.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU therefore considers that section 119 Highways Act 1980 should be amended to ensure that local authorities pay particular regard to a presumption that rights of way should not pass through farmyards or other land where safety, security or nuisance are an issue.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A set period after use has ceased that an ‘established use’ application can be made to register a right of way</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Much of the legislative reform in the draft Deregulation Bill focuses on historical claims to the use of unrecorded rights of way prior to 1949, sometimes referred to as ‘lost ways’. A right of way may also be ‘claimed’ after a period of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">established</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> use. Section 31 of the Highways Act 1980 states that (subject to certain conditions and exceptions) if a path is used as a right of way “as of right” for a period of not less than 20 years, without interruption, the landowner is deemed to have dedicated the right of way, unless it can be shown that the landowner did not intend to dedicate a right of way. After the required period of use has been established, it is possible for an application to be made to have the r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oute added to the Definitive Map</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is currently no time period within which such user claims for public rights of way must be brought. As user claims are calculated from the date the use is “brought into question” this can result in claims for rights of way being made where the 20 years of use is alleged to have taken place 40 or 50 years ago and where no walked route currently exists on the ground. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consequently, even where a landowner has signed a declaration under </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Section 31(6) of the Highways Act 1980</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that they do </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not wish to dedicate any new rights of way on their land, a claim can be made regarding 20 years use predating this declaration.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given the above, it seems reasonable that there should be a time period within which the claim of use must be brought, as is the case with village greens and other areas of law. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, the NFU seeks for a time period for user based claims to a right of way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> similar to those for Town or Village Green Applications under the Section 15 of the Commons Act 2006, which requires claims to be made within 2 years of any cessation of use at present (1 year of cessation as of 1 October 2013 in England). This would provide certainty and clarity for land owners and the public and ensure that claims to a right of way remain in keeping with the most recent land use and function.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">considers that Section 53 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 should be amended to ensure an application made by a person relating to a period of established use must be made within a period of one year from the date the use was brought into question.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Fees or deposits for applications to record</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> or alter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> a right</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">way on a definitive map</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Clause 17 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the draft Deregulation Bill allows flexibility for local authorities to recover costs associated with Public Path Orders to extinguish, divert or modify the status of an existing right of way. Such applications are often made by landowners. Currently local authorities can make charges in-line with charges prescribed by the Secretary of State. Whilst there is some merit in the argument that a more flexible charging regime that enables local authorities to reclaim their costs would facilitate authorities prioritising and completing Public Path Orders, it would not be fair that costs associated with assessing unfounded or “on principle” objections to such modifications should be charged to an applicant. In planning appeals dealt with by written representations costs may be awarded against unreasonable behaviour. Similar suitable safeguards should be built into clause 17, or secondary legislation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Under th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e current process for the recording of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘new’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rights</span><span style="font-family:'Cambria Math'; font-size:11pt">‐</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:'Cambria Math'; font-size:11pt">‐</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">way on a definitive map the costs of determining the application, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">subsequent the inquiry, fall not to the applicant but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Authorities. Moreover, the onus is on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">landowner to provide evidence that disproves statements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">made by the applicants and to pay for legal advice and advocacy at the inquiry.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The report of the Independent Farming Regulation Task Force</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, chaired by Richard Macdonald, recommended that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for application for the recording of new rights</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">way, mechanisms should be introduced to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rebalance the process and to ensure that reasonable costs are met by both parti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es (i.e. including the applicant seeking a right of way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given the above, it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> holds that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">user applicants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should pay a fee when submitting a claim. The situation is analogous to village greens where fees are already charged</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to applicants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">La</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndowners </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">who deposit a statement with their local highway authority</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">under Section 31(6) of the Highways Act 1980</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">protect their land from claims of rights of way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are also subject to a fee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It is inequitable to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">charge in such cases </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">without also ensuring that users also pay either a deposit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a fee towards the costs of their claims for a right of way. In the case of a deposit this could be repaid in the circumstance that a right of way is found to exist based on the body of evidence provided and is added to the definitive map.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, the NFU considers that the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 should be amended to enable provisions for fees or deposits to be payable in relation to the submission of evidence discovered in relation to matters specified under subsection 53 (3)(b), subsection 53(3)(c); and an application under section 53 (5).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Such a fee should be in line with existing fees charged by planning authorities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Clause</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> 16: Gating of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rights of way</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU supports the extension of powers to erect gates or other works on rights of way crossing agricultural land for the purposes of preventing animals coming onto the land or escaping from it to include restricted byways and byways open to all traffic as well as footpaths and bridleways which are already covered.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, Clause 16 as written within the draft Deregulation Bill would not enable the gating of a right of way on the grounds of security. Theft of farm machinery and equipment remains an ever present problem; rural theft cost an estimated £42.3 million in the UK during 2012 with fuel, tools, and farm vehicles the most commonly targeted items</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Security concerns are a common objection of landowners in cases where</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unrecorded right of way </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is claimed on their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> land. Enabling highways authorities to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gates or other works on security grounds would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">allow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> measures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> where locally necessary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to prevent vehicular access </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> prevent trespass and nuisance, access by travelling communities and theft of farm equipment. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In such a scenario the local authority would have discretion in giving authorisation, and would need to be satisfied that it was expedient that such structures should be erected on the right of way before authorising them.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU considers that Section 147 of the Highways Act 1980 should be amended to enable authorities to authorise structures on a right of way for any reasonable purpose including agriculture, security and protection of property</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">mprov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the quality of evidence to ju</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">stify claims</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At present the test applied by a local authority at the initial order making stage for an unrecorded route is that a route is “reasonably alleged” to subsist. However, the order can only be confirmed if it is found “on the balance of probabilities” to subsist. The use of the lower threshold in earlier tests results in confusion, as well as wasted time, money and resources in making orders for claims which will not succeed on the balance of probabilities. The NFU believes the “balance of probabilities” test should be used consistently throughout</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and successful claims should carry a sufficient quality and quantity of evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Therefore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the NFU strongly supports Schedule 6, Paragraph 2 of the draft Deregulation Bill removing the wording “reasonably alleged to subsist” from Section 53(3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c)(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) of the Wildlife &amp; Countryside Act 1981.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, with user claims for an ‘established period of use’ of a right of way it is important that the evidence submitted is a statement of truth. Authorities must have confidence that claims made are genuine; witness statements in support of a claim should be individually completed. Therefore, the NFU would support an amendment to ensure that when submitting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">documentary evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that inc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lud</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> statements of witnesses in support of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> application each witness has completed their own statement and signed a statement of truth.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Clause</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> 43: </span><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary-Bold; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Gangmasters</span><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary-Bold; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (Licensing) Act 2004: enforcement</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU supports </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clause</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 43 of the draft Bill which will enable the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Gangmasters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Licencing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Authority to have access to Enforcement Undertaking civil sanctions in addition to their current powers. This support is conditional upon the civil sanction procedure containing protections against any abuse of power or error by the inclusion of accessible review and appeal procedures.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Clause</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> 58: </span><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary-Bold; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Exercise of regulatory functions: economic growth</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU agrees in principle with a standard “contribute to economic growth and prosperity duty”, which should apply to all regulators.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many regulators will have principles within their functions, remit or Ministerial guidance relating to openness or transparency, the need to support business to comply with regulation and to protect the economy.  Many of these could be updated to reflect the current needs in respect of deficit reductions, regulating only where necessary and promoting growth, which would support many of the existing functions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Introducing a more specific duty for growth through legislation would enable leaders throughout the agencies and regulators in scope to more confidently deliver policy and support prosperity in partnership with business. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU believe that regulators should see their role as supporting prosperity as well as environmental protection or protecting human health.  We would expect regulatory agencies to have an objective role in policy delivery and statutory safeguard and a new explicit role in determining how economic growth, prosperity and food security can be promoted without damage to the environment, or reduced food and operator safety risks.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The key changes that we would envisage impacting on a regulator as a result of the growth duty would largely be around a shift in attitudes and connection with the business community.  This should result in greater awareness of the impacts of regulation on enterprise across the regulated sector, and more meaningful, open engagement with stakeholders.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To help facilitate these changes we would expect that any duty will need to be matched by improving the necessary skills, experience and knowledge of regulatory staff.  Regular, on-going training and knowledge exchange can help regulators have a greater understanding of farming and the pressures and impact of external factors such as the weather and what this could mean to profitability in the future.  This impacts on the relative empathy and understanding of the sector and does much to shape a regulators relationship with the sector.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have no evidence to suggest that a growth duty will add significant burdens to regulators</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would expect that any growth duty will need to provide a stronger focus for how regulators interact with business.  This needs to be part of broader engagement to help regulators understand the dynamics, drivers and issues of those businesses they regulate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A growth duty should have a beneficial effect in terms of reducing costs to business where possible and remove or address barriers to growth and regulatory burdens.  This is an important area if we are to create a competitive and resilient agriculture industry, with the cost of regulation currently representing around one-tenth of an average farms net profit.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU would suggest that the financial and economic impact of the proposed duty can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assessed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through a framework allowing for comparison between different regulators.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The indicators on the framework could include assessment of trends in business sector performance (aggregate profitability/GVA/jobs); understanding of key challenges facing the sector; periodic assessment of how activities undertaken by regulatory bodies shape growth (both positive and negative); and engagement with stakeholders for on-going review to capture how bodies support the growth agenda with communication to highlight positive activity.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0.5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAq4AAAACCAYAAACZvl66AAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAABBSURBVFhH7dZBDQAwCARB6gpL+BdAwUWbzCUYmOyDiNmpbMdAAxrQgAY0oAENaODVBvZnNQIECBAgQIAAAQJfCFzJnlppS4/FSwAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==" width="686" height="2" alt="" style="margin-left:0pt; margin-top:-1.8pt; position:absolute; z-index:-65536" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> A group with representatives of landowners, Local Authorities and pro</span><span style="font-family:'Cambria Math'; font-size:10pt">‐</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">access groups</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">brought together by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> and Natural England </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">to improve the process by which unrecorded rights of way are added to the Definitive Map</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> and Statement. The report was published in March 2010. See </span><a href="http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/40012"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/40012</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> The report of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Independent Farming Regulation Task Force</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> - Striking a balance: reducing burdens; increasing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">responsibility</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">; earning recognition. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">A report on better regulation in farming and food businesses.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/69201/pb13527-farm-reg-task-report.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/69201/pb13527-farm-reg-task-report.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">NFU Mutual Rural Crime Survey 2013</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> - </span><a href="http://www.nfumutual.co.uk/farming/initiatives/rural-crime/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times N